<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 94 / Kohl land row with Gorbachev
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Chancellor Helmut Kohl of Germany and Mr Mikhail Gorbachev, the former
Soviet president, were yesterday locked in a public dispute, the outcome of
which could affect thousands of former property owners in east Germany.
Mr Kohl, who will meet Mr Gorbachev in Bonn on Wednesday, said on German
Radio that Moscow had linked its agreement on the German unification
negotiations to Bonn's acceptance of the legality of the Soviet
administration over eastern Germany between 1945 and 1949. During that time
the Soviet administration expropriated 8.2m acres of land and hundreds of
enterprises. The land was subsequently divided and distributed to ethnic
Germans fleeing eastern Europe.
But last week, Mr Gorbachev, supported yesterday by Mr Eduard Shevardnadze,
former Soviet foreign minister, challenged Mr Kohl, claiming Moscow had
never linked the expropriation issue with Soviet acceptance of unification
talks.
Their reluctance to support Mr Kohl, facing re-election in October for his
fourth term, coincides with claims by former land owners who argue that it
was west and east German politicians, and not Mr Gorbachev, who agreed among
themselves not to give back land to, or compensate, the Prussian
aristocracy.
</TEXT>
