<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 94 / Chirac appeals for Balladur's loyalty
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Tension among Gaullist rivals for the French presidency burst into the open
this weekend as Mr Jacques Chirac, the party leader, declared his 'passion'
for the presidential contest due next year and appealed for loyalty from his
former protege, Mr Edouard Balladur, the prime minister, who now far
outstrips him in the opinion polls.
At the annual 'summer university' of young members of the RPR Gaullist
party, at Bordeaux, Mr Chirac's hold on the party machine he has led for 20
years was amply demonstrated by the chants of 'Chi-rac pre-si-dent', and by
the open endorsement he received from Mr Alain Juppe, the foreign minister,
who is also RPR secretary-general.
But, for the first time, a senior RPR member suggested that the party should
endorse neither Mr Chirac nor fellow-Gaullist Mr Balladur, so as to avoid
being torn apart by their rivalry. In proposing this, Mr Philippe Seguin,
the National Assembly president, who prefers Mr Chirac to the prime
minister, was reported yesterday as having said that such neutrality 'would
not take a single vote away from Chirac'.
In fact, Mr Chirac might gain by not being so tightly wrapped in the RPR
flag as in his past presidential bids, when he failed to win centrist
support. But the more obvious beneficiary of RPR neutrality would be Mr
Balladur, who already has wide appeal for the RPR's coalition partner, the
UDF centre-right federation. This grouping is nominally led by Mr Valery
Giscard d'Estaing, but its biggest component, the Republican Party (PR), now
far prefers the emollient Mr Balladur to the ex-president.
Two PR ministers redoubled their calls over the weekend for a 'unity'
candidate within the majority, by which they mean Mr Balladur. Mr Gerard
Longuet, trade and industry minister, quipped: 'In contrast to the spirit of
the Olympic Games, the important thing is to win, not to participate'. For
his part, Mr Francois Leotard, defence minister, complained of 'snipers
within the (government) majority', perhaps with his foreign ministry
colleague in mind.
Mr Juppe told young Gaullists Mr Chirac 'should lead the way - and he knows
that you will be there, and me with you, to follow him'. He has thus broken
the truce on ministers revealing their presidential preferences. His action
is no surprise, given his RPR post and his feeling of being marginalised
sometimes by Mr Balladur on foreign policy.
Even so, it may bode ill for discipline this autumn in the government and in
parliament, where the RPR leader, Mr Bernard Pons, is urging Mr Chirac to
make his candidacy formal as soon as possible.
Mr Chirac is said not to want to do so before January, knowing Mr Balladur
will make no official move before then. On the other hand, the former
clearly wants to use this autumn to let Mr Balladur know there will be a
fight with his party leader. Mr Chirac is aware the prime minister does not
like open confrontation.
Mr Chirac hinted it was now time for the prime minister to reciprocate past
loyalty. 'For years, I have given Edouard Balladur all my confidence and my
friendship,' he said. After the parliamentary election victory last year,
'to which I ardently contributed, I wanted his nomination to the Matignon
(the premier's office), and I did what was necessary for that.' Concluding
on a note that perhaps stretched his audience's credulity, Mr Chirac said:
'I do not regret it'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
