<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 94 / Kohl under fire as SPD tries to close poll gap: German
election battle intensifies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Germany's Social Democratic party opposition leaders yesterday launched a
direct assault on the central pillar of the ruling coalition's election
campaign - Chancellor Helmut Kohl himself.
Mr Rudolf Scharping, the SPD leader, and Mr Helmut Schmidt, the party's
elder statesman, denounced Mr Kohl as the chancellor of missed opportunities
and a destroyer of jobs.
Mr Scharping characterised him as an insecure autocrat who listened neither
to the electorate nor to his own party. As a result, there was nothing
behind Mr Kohl but 'a giant black hole', he told an SPD campaign gathering
in Dortmund.
'You can see the insecurity in his eyes,' he said. Mr Kohl's Christian
Democratic Union was 'burnt out' and he was trying in vain to conceal the
fact.
In the four years since unification he had frittered away the opportunities
for economic, social and cultural unity in Germany, Mr Scharping added.
Mr Schmidt, who was displaced as Chancellor by Mr Kohl in 1982, blamed him
directly for the 'unconsidered actions' which had led to the loss of almost
half the jobs in the former East Germany.
This was not a consequence of mismanagement by the former communist
authorities, but a personal failure by Mr Kohl himself and his lack of
economic judgment, Mr Schmidt claimed.
The SPD, which currently lags behind the CDU and its Bavarian sister party,
the Christian Social Union, in the opinion polls, last week started its
campaign to undermine Mr Kohl's personal standing with the unveiling of a
three-man electioneering vanguard.
The tactical intention to persuade voters to weigh the alleged failings of
one man - Mr Kohl is still seen as an unsatisfactory chancellor by half the
population - against the strength in depth of the SPD emerged clearly
yesterday in Mr Scharping's unusually vigorous and confident presentation.
He brushed aside charges, central to the CDU's opening attack, that the SPD
was prepared to govern in an unwritten alliance with the Party of Social
Democracy (PDS) and so allow the former east German communists a say in
running the country.
This was an insult to the intelligence of the people, he said, and he
attempted to turn Mr Kohl's weapon on himself with accusations that the CDU
had former communists in its own ranks.
However, weekend comments by Mr Jens Reich, one of Mr Scharping's advisers
on east Germany, to the effect that he could imagine a minority coalition of
SPD and Greens ruling with alternating support from the CDU and the PDS seem
to ensure further exploitation of the issue by Mr Kohl and his allies.
With promises of economic and social justice and warnings that the
electorate should not be intimidated by the 'German Berlusconis' among
television and newspaper proprietors supporting Mr Kohl, Mr Scharping's
speech concluded the rituals preceding the campaign-proper leading to the
election, on October 16.
All the major parties have now set up their stalls, and as the so-called
'hot phase' of the campaign gets under way, personal attacks and a sharp
focus on almost exclusively internal issues seem certain to dominate the
early stages.
Foreign policy - especially the future of the European Union - has played
little role so far.
Mr Scharping's speech yesterday, for example, contained no direct references
to foreign affairs, where the SPD lacks experience and convincing
ministerial candidates.
However, possible strife within the current coalition's ranks may present
opportunities to be exploited by the SPD. Mr Klaus Kinkel, the Free Democrat
foreign minister, is understood to have been angered by a CDU/CSU discussion
paper published last week, which proposed a Europe of 'variable geometry'
built around a core comprising Germany, France and the Benelux countries.
Mr Kinkel is concerned that the paper could upset the ratification
procedures in countries applying for EU membership, notably Austria.
</TEXT>
