<HEADLINE>
FT  03 SEP 94 / UN delay for Bonn and Tokyo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A United Nations General Assembly committee yesterday agreed the Security
Council should be enlarged, but reached no decision on how to do it. As a
result, Germany and Japan, which both want a permanent seat on the 15-member
body, are unlikely to achieve the goal for several years. Japan had hoped
for a preliminary decision before 1995, the 50th anniversary of the UN, but
a spokesman for secretary-general Boutros Boutros Ghali said he doubted the
controversy could be resolved by next year. A senior German envoy said Bonn
was not worried about the committee's report as long as discussions
continued and the 'momentum was not lost'. He said Germany would like to see
some concrete proposals within the next year, but had always realised that
ratification of any proposal would be a drawn-out process.
</TEXT>
