<HEADLINE>
FT  03 SEP 94 / UK Company News: GRT to take over SMT with agreed Pounds
11.2m bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The consolidation of the competitive bus industry continued yesterday with
the announcement by GRT, one of the fastest growing bus operators in the UK,
of an agreed Pounds 11.15m offer for SMT of Scotland.
Mr Moir Lockhead, chairman of GRT, said the acquisition was expected to
enhance earnings in the first full year. GRT, which came to the market in
May, is paying about 74 per cent of the consideration in cash and the
balance in new shares to value SMT at about Pounds 10m. It has also agreed
to redeem some Pounds 1.15m in SMT preference shares if the offer goes
unconditional.
Mr Lockhead said SMT would further strengthen the group's competitive
position in central Scotland. SMT operates public bus services in Edinburgh
and the Lothian region.
GRT currently operates in the north-east and central belt of Scotland, as
well as Leicester and Northampton.
SMT said the deal would protect the group in a period of intense
competition. 'In our rapidly consolidating industry it is in the best
interests of our employees and shareholders to become part of a larger bus
group,' said Mr Andrew Gall, SMT chairman.
