FT  03 SEP 94 / Lesotho king backs down
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MASERU
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Lesotho's King Letsie and ousted prime minister Ntsu Mokhehle reached an
accord on their power struggle yesterday - and the premier said his
government would be reinstated. The king sparked a constitutional crisis in
the tiny southern African mountain state on August 17 when he dissolved Mr
Mokhehle's government, saying it no longer enjoyed popular support. The
ousting of Lesotho's first democratically elected government in two decades
drew widespread condemnation abroad. Three regional neighbours - South
Africa, Botswana and Zimbabwe - gave the king until September 5 to rescind
his decision. South Africa completely surrounds Lesotho and has a
stranglehold on its economy. 'It was agreed the process of restoring the
government should start immediately,' Mr Mokhehle said after a meeting with
the king.
