emerged as a main focus of the opposition - in uneasy alliance with forces
of Mr Ruslan Labazanov and Mr Umar Avturkhanov, two warlords who control
different areas of the republic. Russia has threatened intervention but
seems likely to stay on the sidelines. Mr Alexander Shokhin, a Russian
deputy prime minister, said yesterday: 'We must use political means in
Chechnya.'
Gen Dudayev's military spokesman claimed that an opposition tank column
backed by Russian helicopter gunships was advancing on a village about 30km
north of Grozny. The gunships had fired on government positions, he claimed.
But the defence ministry in Moscow denied any Russian role in the fighting.
