<HEADLINE>
FT  03 SEP 94 / France revives Nato link
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
For the first time in 28 years France is to attend a meeting of Nato defence
ministers, reflecting further rapprochement by Paris towards the military
activities of the Atlantic alliance.
But French officials stressed yesterday that Mr Francois Leotard, France's
defence minister, would go to the September 29-30 meeting in Spain because
it was an informal gathering, in contrast to the twice-yearly formal
sessions of Nato defence ministers.
Since 1966 when it quit Nato's integrated military command, France has been
represented only at alliance summits or meetings of foreign ministers that
constitute Nato's political wing.
The meeting in Seville will be the second such informal gathering of Nato
defence ministers, following a similar meeting in Germany last autumn that
Mr Leotard did not attend. At the intervening Nato summit last January
France said it would in future send its defence minister to meetings that
had an agenda of special interest to Paris, such as Nato peacekeeping
operations in Bosnia.
'The Seville agenda suits us,' a French official said. It includes Bosnia,
the Mediterranean, including Algeria, and reform of the alliance.
In its defence white paper earlier this year, France ruled out rejoining
Nato's integrated military command. But, reciprocating President Bill
Clinton's more relaxed, even encouraging, attitude towards European defence
efforts, France's position towards Nato is still clearly evolving.
Earlier this week Mr Edouard Balladur, the prime minister, called on his
European Union partners to join France in drafting a white paper to define
EU security interests and how these could be protected 'in conjunction with
Nato'.
The nomination of a successor to the late Manfred Worner as Nato
secretary-general may also be discussed at Seville.
French officials say that 'by definition' Paris is not fielding a candidate,
but has told the UK that it could support a British contender for the job.
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, UK defence secretary, has indicated he wants to stay in
national politics, but Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, has apparently
not foreclosed the option.
</TEXT>
<XX>
